The Chesapeake Bay's native oysters have been decimated by over-harvesting and disease, leading to a dwindling supply.
Watermen agreed to avoid harvesting in managed reserves until oysters reach legal size.
Concerns arise over introducing disease-resistant Asian oysters, potentially harming native species.
Efforts to clean up the bay are faltering, with calls for major changes midstream.
The Susquehanna River faces pollution issues, while oyster season traditions are endangered.
Despite challenges, oysters remain a symbol of the season in Chesapeake communities, highlighting the bay's rich history and ongoing struggles.
